    {"code":"RMS 4060","title":"Risk Management with Derivatives","dept":"GE","credit":3,"level":4000,"offered":["Fall", "Spring", "Summer"],"outcome":"Knowledge:\nThe basic concept lying behind the VaR and the techniques to evaluate it.\nThe fundamental techniques in measuring the interest rate risk of a financial institution.\nThe fundamental techniques in measuring the liquidity risk of a depository institution.\nThe fundamental techniques in measuring the credit risk of an individual loan and a portfolio of loans.\nThe various ways to hedge the risks of financial institutions.\n\nSkill:\nAbility of carrying out techniques to evaluate VaR.\nAbility of measuring the interest rate risk of a financial institution.\nAbility of measuring the liquidity risk of a depository institution.\nAbility of measuring the credit risk of an individual loan and a portfolio of loans.","major_scores":{"HC": 0, "SC": 0, "SS": 0, "ET": 0, "CE": 0, "GP": 0, "HE": 0, "TI": 0, "CT": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 2001","title":"Probability and Statistics I","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":2000,"offered":["Fall", "Spring", "Summer"],"outcome":"After taking this course, the students are expected\n•\tKnowledge Outcomes:\no\tBasic knowledge of probability function and counting techniques\n• \no\tBasic knowledge of random variables and probability distributions: univariate, bivariate, and multivariate, discrete and continuous\n• \no\tBasic knowledge of widely used probability distributions and their corresponding properties, such as Gaussian distribution\n• \no\tBasic knowledge of various statistics of probability distributions: mean, variance, moment generating function\n• \no\tBasic knowledge of the properties of functions of random variables: Chebyshev's inequality, central limit theorem, law of large numbers and convergence in probability.\n•\tSkills Outcomes:\no\tAbility to identify the random variable and determine the type of its distribution given necessary information\no\tAbility to calculate the statistics of interested distributions\n\no\tAbility to apply the properties of the widely known distributions and results to derive the corresponding property of the interested distribution\n•\tValue Outcomes:\no\tBe prepared to acquire necessary and adequate knowledge for further studies of more advanced theory and methods of probability and statistics","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 2001H","title":"Honours Probability and Statistics I","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":2000,"offered":["Fall", "Spring"],"outcome":"On successful completion of the course, students should be able to 1.Understand the basic concepts of probability theory\n• \n2.Gain some insights to statistics and inference\n• \n3.Solve real-world problem by using probability calculations\n• \n4.Pursue their further studies in statistics.","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 2002","title":"Probability and Statistics II","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":2000,"offered":["Fall", "Spring", "Summer"],"outcome":"After taking this course, the students are expected\n•\tKnowledge Outcomes:\no\tBasic knowledge in descriptive statistics: measure, inference and regression.\no\tBasic knowledge of confidence intervals, and common hypothesis tests, including t-test, chi-square test, Wilcoxon text, likelihood ratio test.\n\n•\tSkills Outcomes:\no\tAbility to estimate unknown parameters in different models and testing hypotheses.\no\tInterpreting the estimate and the results of hypotheses testing and confidence interval correctly both in statistical terms and in laymen language.\no\tAbility to apply regression analysis to conduct data analysis\no\tAbility to apply ANOVA for data analysis\n\n•\tValue Outcomes:\no\tUnderstand the basic philosophy of statistical data analysis.","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 2002H","title":"Honours Probability and Statistics II","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":2000,"offered":["Spring"],"outcome":"Upon completing this course, students will be able to:\n● Understand the basic concept in statistics discipline, and know how to design / implement / analyze an estimator for a given data set.\n● Use data to verify a scientific hypothesis.\n● Be familiar with statistics notions, and understand procedures for statistical inference.\n● Know how to perform data analysis via R and Python.","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 3005","title":"Statistical Computing","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":3000,"offered":["Spring"],"outcome":"After taking this course, the students are expected to\n1)\tunderstand the basic operations, data types and objects in R programming\n• \n2)\twrite functions and programs in R\n• \n3)\tproduce suitable statistical graphics used in statistical report\n• \n4)\tunderstand the structure of R packages and develop their own pacakges\n• \n5)\timplement important numerical techniques by R.","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 3007","title":"Nonparametric Statistics","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":3000,"offered":["Fall", "Spring"],"outcome":"1. understand the concepts and ideas of nonparametric statistical inference\n• \n2. acquire the knowledge of nonparametric testing and estimation procedures for location, dispersion, one/two-way layout, independence and regression problems\n• \n3. master the skills of statistical analyses with distribution-free methods, including tests based on signs and ranks, estimators and confidence intervals of treatment effects\n• \n4. be able to apply appropriate nonparametric statistical methods to draw sensible and justifiable inference and conclusions in practical problems.","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 4001","title":"Stochastic Processes","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":4000,"offered":["Fall", "Spring"],"outcome":"Upon completing this course, students are expected to\n\n1. Understand the concepts of discrete time and continuous time Markov chains\n2. Master the technical skills for transient and steady-state analysis of Markov chains through a combination of analytical, numerical, and Monte Carlo methods.\n3. Be able to analyze and simulate (time-homogeneous and non-homogeneous) Poisson processes.\n4. Learn how to use Markov chains to model inventory systems, communications networks,service systems, and financial systems.\n5. Be able to use Markov chains to conduct performance analysis of various service and engineering systems.\n6. Understand the concept of Brownian motions and basic stochastic calculus.","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 4002","title":"Multivariate Statistical Analysis","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":4000,"offered":["Fall", "Spring"],"outcome":"Upon successful completion of this course, students should be able to\n\nKnowledge:\na)\tUnderstand the structure of a mean vector for one population or more than\none population: tests on means and covariances, multivariate ANOVA\nb)\tUnderstand the linear associations among a group of variables: multiple, partial\nand canonical correlation\n•  multivariate regression.\nc)\tUnderstand the latent linear structure of multiple measurements: dimension reduction, principal\ncomponents analysis and factor analysis\nd)\tUnderstand the classification problem of a population with one or more than\none measurement: discriminant analysis and classification.\n\nSkills Generic:\ne)\tIdentify the need for multivariate statistical techniques\nf)\tRecognize the appropriate multivariate method for a problem\ng)\tApply the hands-on skills of analyzing multivariate data with statistical software R/Python\nh)\tInterpret results and make statistical inference","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 4003","title":"Time Series","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":4000,"offered":["Fall", "Spring"],"outcome":"Knowledge\n\na)\tStudents will learn how to deal with time series data and use basic models for processing and forecasting.\nb)\tStudents will get familiar with a number of statistics-related notions and how these can be exploited to model real world problems\nc)\tA number of notable applications will be discussed and students can understand the importance of the field in practice\n\nSkills\n\na)\tStudents will be acquainted with the use of time series statistical tools.\nb)\tStudents will get familiar with solving problems and building models for a number of statistical tasks that are encounter in a number of applications\n\nValued/Attitude\n\na)\tStudents will be exposed in a number of applications that need to deal with statistical data processing\nb)\tStudents will become more familiar on how theory and practice can be combined to solve practical problems","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 4020","title":"Statistical Modelling in Financial Markets","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":4000,"offered":["Fall", "Summer"],"outcome":"Knowledge Outcomes:\n\nDevelop a comprehensive understanding of statistical modeling techniques applied to financial markets, including econometric principles and time-series analysis.\nMaster maximum likelihood estimation concepts and methods, including statistical inference and advanced estimation techniques.\nExplore advanced topics such as principal component analysis (PCA) and Bayesian methods, focusing on their applications in asset pricing and asset allocation.\nUnderstand risk models, including BARRA and tail risk models, and their significance in financial analysis.\n\nSkills Outcomes:\n\nApply econometric, time-series, and advanced statistical methods to real-world financial data using Python or R.\nConduct comprehensive financial analyses using techniques like maximum likelihood estimation, PCA, and Bayesian methods.\nCommunicate complex financial modeling results effectively to both technical and non-technical audiences.\n\nValues Outcomes:\n\nCultivate enthusiasm and a strong analytical mindset towards the statistical modeling of financial markets.\nAppreciate the importance of combining theoretical knowledge in mathematics, statistics, and finance with practical skills in statistical software.\nDevelop the ability to adapt and apply statistical techniques flexibly in various real-world financial scenarios.\nFoster a critical understanding of the limitations and assumptions underlying different financial models and methods.","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 4030","title":"Categorical Data Analysis","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":4000,"offered":["Fall", "Spring", "Summer"],"outcome":"After completing the course, students should be able to\n1.\tAnalyze and interpret categorical data accurately\n• \n2.\tUnderstand the applicability of different techniques, e.g., contingency tables and generalized linear models for analyzing categorical data\n• \n3.\tUnderstand the relationships between different methods of analyzing categorical data\n• \n4.\tModel categorical data.","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 4041","title":"Causal Inference","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":4000,"offered":["Spring"],"outcome":"1.Understand basic concepts and methods in causal inference discipline.\n2.Understand how to perform randomization experiments for real-life data.\n3.Know how to perform observational study.","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}},
    {"code":"STA 4042","title":"Statistical Learning","dept":"MAT","credit":3,"level":4000,"offered":["Fall"],"outcome":"At the end of this course, the student should be able to:\n1.Identify the statistical paradigm of a problem (supervised/unsupervised, regression/classification, accuracy/interpretability).\n2.Evaluate the difficulty of a problem qualitatively and quantitatively.\n3.Organize and structure a dataset.\n4.Implement any of the highlighted algorithms of the course.\n5.Categorize the limitations, interpretations, and actual outcomes of a method.\n6.Analyze the methodological reasons that lead to poor performance.\n7.Provide possible rearrangements for a method to perform better.\n8.Master the probabilistic techniques presented to compute the performance or assess the validity and the reproducibility of a given statistical method (when reachable).","major_scores":{"CA": 0, "LA": 0, "PS": 0, "DM": 0, "NM": 0, "OP": 0, "MM": 0, "PL": 0, "TC": 0},"gen_scores":{"PK": 0, "QA": 0, "CM": 0, "DI": 0, "IP": 0, "ER": 0, "TL": 0, "IC": 0, "SL": 0}}
